# Steps to reproduce the problem
See problem description.

# Problem Description
With a WebGL2 stream of commands like:

```
const tex = gl.createTexture();

gl.bindTexture(gl.TEXTURE_2D, tex);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_MAG_FILTER, gl.NEAREST);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_MIN_FILTER, gl.NEAREST);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_WRAP_S, gl.CLAMP_TO_EDGE);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_WRAP_T, gl.CLAMP_TO_EDGE);
gl.texStorage2D(gl.TEXTURE_2D, 1, gl.R32UI, width, height);

const view = new Uint32Array(<texture data>);
gl.texSubImage2D(gl.TEXTURE_2D, 0, 0, 0, width, height, gl.RED_INTEGER, gl.UNSIGNED_INT, view);

<set vertex array>
<set program>
<set program constants>

gl.drawArrays(gl.TRIANGLES, <baseVertex>, <numVertices>);

// Feed the same texture with new data:

const new_view = new Uint32Array(<new texture data>);
gl.texSubImage2D(gl.TEXTURE_2D, 0, 0, 0, width, height, gl.RED_INTEGER, gl.UNSIGNED_INT, new_view);

<set vertex array>
<set program>
<set program constants>

gl.drawArrays(gl.TRIANGLES, <baseVertex>, <numVertices>);
```

Sometimes, on MacOS, at random, produces strange artifacts like if 2nd `drawArrays` does not realize the texture content changed after 1st `drawArrays`.

If I create a new texture overy time, the program behaves correctly:

```
const tex = gl.createTexture();

gl.bindTexture(gl.TEXTURE_2D, tex);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_MAG_FILTER, gl.NEAREST);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_MIN_FILTER, gl.NEAREST);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_WRAP_S, gl.CLAMP_TO_EDGE);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_WRAP_T, gl.CLAMP_TO_EDGE);
gl.texStorage2D(gl.TEXTURE_2D, 1, gl.R32UI, width, height);

const view = new Uint32Array(<texture data>);
gl.texSubImage2D(gl.TEXTURE_2D, 0, 0, 0, width, height, gl.RED_INTEGER, gl.UNSIGNED_INT, view);

<set vertex array>
<set program>
<set program constants>

gl.drawArrays(gl.TRIANGLES, <baseVertex>, <numVertices>);

// Feed the **new** texture with new data:
const new_tex = gl.createTexture();

gl.bindTexture(gl.TEXTURE_2D, new_tex);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_MAG_FILTER, gl.NEAREST);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_MIN_FILTER, gl.NEAREST);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_WRAP_S, gl.CLAMP_TO_EDGE);
gl.texParameteri(gl.TEXTURE_2D, gl.TEXTURE_WRAP_T, gl.CLAMP_TO_EDGE);
gl.texStorage2D(gl.TEXTURE_2D, 1, gl.R32UI, width, height);

const new_view = new Uint32Array(<new texture data>);
gl.texSubImage2D(gl.TEXTURE_2D, 0, 0, 0, width, height, gl.RED_INTEGER, gl.UNSIGNED_INT, new_view);

<set vertex array>
<set program>
<set program constants>

gl.drawArrays(gl.TRIANGLES, <baseVertex>, <numVertices>);
```

I was not able to repro on Windows.

I also tried to insert a `gl.flush()` in between draw calls, but that helps just in some cases (e.g. even with explicit `gl.flush()` sometimes I got screen artifacts).

# Summary
`drawArrays` not reflecting updates in `texSubImage2d` on MacOS | Intel.

